              "id": "QUE58580",
              "question": "What makes defining classes in U.S. society so difficult?\n\u003cbr /\u003e",
              "order": "randomized",
              "presenterType": "RadioGroup",
              "presenterConfig": {
                "numberFormat": "none"
              },
              "choices": [
                {
                  "answerKey": "answer_1",
                  "content": "The controlling class does not want to be classified for fear of sparking political revolt."
                },
                {
                  "answerKey": "answer_2",
                  "content": "People believe themselves to be in a higher class than they really are."
                },
                {
                  "answerKey": "answer_3",
                  "content": "Although people believe the United States does not have a caste system, it does in fact have a very rigid one."
                },
                {
                  "answerKey": "answer_4",
                  "content": "U.S. society has a relatively low level of status consistency so the boundaries between class levels are not very clear."
